    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1494842608" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1494842608" />
    <a title="Mj" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5706631-mj"><img alt="Mj" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1323026745p2/5706631.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1494842608?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mj" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mj" href="/user/show/5706631-mj">Mj</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5706631-mj?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5706631-mj?shelf=2015">2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1494842608" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13469753534900516511">I read Doubt, A Parable, as part of a book challenge. It was a 2005 Pulitzer Prize Winner in the category of drama. While short in terms of pages, it is long with respect to impact, creating tension and provoking thought – quite masterful really for so few words.<br/> <br/>As a drama, the book is 99% dialogue interspersed with stage directions. It features only four characters. And yet, the author is able to craft a tightly written mystery filled with interest and drama. It reads very much like an absorbi</span>
  <span id="freeText13469753534900516511" style="display:none">I read Doubt, A Parable, as part of a book challenge. It was a 2005 Pulitzer Prize Winner in the category of drama. While short in terms of pages, it is long with respect to impact, creating tension and provoking thought – quite masterful really for so few words.<br /> <br />As a drama, the book is 99% dialogue interspersed with stage directions. It features only four characters. And yet, the author is able to craft a tightly written mystery filled with interest and drama. It reads very much like an absorbing detective procedural. <br /><br />Doubt is an issues driven play that focuses on moral dilemmas and the determination of guilt and innocence. It doesn’t preach or even take a position. Rather the story and writing constantly raises questions by causing one to stop and think. After finishing the book, I am still thinking and not quite sure that I am comfortable that the process to resolution was justified despite the supposedly correct resolution (which is also up in the air for me.) I think this conundrum is the integral ingredient that makes the play work. The play makes one realize that life is much more grey than white and black - murky sort of. If I ever get a chance to see Doubt staged live, I will definitely be in the audience and will also be looking into more of John Patrick Shanley’s work. It turns out there was a film version made of Doubt with the screenplay written and movie directed by Shanley <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0918927/?ref_=ttawd_awd_tt">http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0918927/?...</a><br /><br />After looking further, it turns out that Shanley has written a number of other plays for stage and screenplays for film and has won a number of nominations and awards for his work. Doubt, A Parable has piqued my interest. Shanley is one impressive playwright.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13469753534900516511" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

