<div id="review_1473943617" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1473943617" />
    <a title="Mary Slowik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4404773-mary-slowik"><img alt="Mary Slowik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451700888p2/4404773.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1473943617?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mary Slowik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mary Slowik" href="/user/show/4404773-mary-slowik">Mary Slowik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Playwrights-in-training</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4404773-mary-slowik?shelf=borrowed">borrowed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4404773-mary-slowik?shelf=drama">drama</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1473943617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12461668380616412775">December of Drama 2015, day nineteen<br/><br/>&quot;<i>I think of what you do all day<br/>I wonder if what you say is true<br/>You always get what you want<br/>I can&apos;t trust you</i>&quot;<br/>--True Lies, by The New Division<br/><br/>My oh my. This is drama in the truest sense. Tight and intense and honest. It rolls along with the momentum of conflict growing all the time (stakes being raised) and plenty of gasp-inducing moments for the audience. My four star rating doesn&apos;t indicate that I think there&apos;s anything wrong with the play-- it&apos;s flawless. Ma</span>
  <span id="freeText12461668380616412775" style="display:none">December of Drama 2015, day nineteen<br /><br />"<i>I think of what you do all day<br />I wonder if what you say is true<br />You always get what you want<br />I can't trust you</i>"<br />--True Lies, by The New Division<br /><br />My oh my. This is drama in the truest sense. Tight and intense and honest. It rolls along with the momentum of conflict growing all the time (stakes being raised) and plenty of gasp-inducing moments for the audience. My four star rating doesn't indicate that I think there's anything wrong with the play-- it's flawless. Maybe I just wanted more of it. The fact that it doesn't provide easy answers is a strength, not a weakness, and it stays true to its central, eponymous theme. In fact, it's not easy... it's <i>un</i>easy. Unsettling. It's been polished until it's a mirror of perfect clarity, forcing the audience to regard its own reflection.<br /><br />I confess, I first saw the adaptation starring Meryl Streep and Philip Seymour Hoffman (and Amy Adams, was it?), so I couldn't help but picture them in the main roles. I don't think anything was left out... this is only 60-some pages, so in truth they had to expand it rather than condense it for the movie. As timely as this subject was circa 2005, there was the obvious risk that this would come off preachy (is that a pun?), but it's not preachy at all. The only point it stresses is to think. And, therefore, to doubt.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12461668380616412775" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


