<div id="review_128228404" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/128228404" />
    <a title="Laura Grable" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3776663-laura-grable"><img alt="Laura Grable" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1274729856p2/3776663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/128228404?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura Grable" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura Grable" href="/user/show/3776663-laura-grable">Laura Grable</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer128228404&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer128228404" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4066578529506196528">I love modern drama and I can definitely see why this won the Pulitzer for Drama when it came out in 2005. It is amazing how well developed these characters feel in 50 short pages. <br/><br/>This play tackled the issue of Catholic priests exploiting young boys, but it is set in 1964 when the issue was ignored by the church and the nuns, if they did happen to notice anything, were seen as inferior to the men and, thus, unable to stop the problem. <br/><br/>Of course though, the main theme of this play is &quot;doubt&quot; and</span>
  <span id="freeText4066578529506196528" style="display:none">I love modern drama and I can definitely see why this won the Pulitzer for Drama when it came out in 2005. It is amazing how well developed these characters feel in 50 short pages. <br /><br />This play tackled the issue of Catholic priests exploiting young boys, but it is set in 1964 when the issue was ignored by the church and the nuns, if they did happen to notice anything, were seen as inferior to the men and, thus, unable to stop the problem. <br /><br />Of course though, the main theme of this play is "doubt" and the playwright purposely leaves you and the characters in doubt as to whether or not a sin was actually committed. It really makes you think about our society and how we must somehow draw a line between our accusatory nature and the danger of ignorance. Overall, it was an excellent play to read and, I imagine, even more of an excellent play to watch.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4066578529506196528" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


