<div id="review_3425688621" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3425688621" />
    <a title="Laura Peña" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39878874-laura-pe-a"><img alt="Laura Peña" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641861492p2/39878874.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3425688621?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura Peña" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura Peña" href="/user/show/39878874-laura-pe-a">Laura Peña</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780822222194" href="/book/show/3151379-doubt">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3425688621" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17776285178419240782">cw sexual assault. Super short play that I read partially because it was short and partially bc I thought it might be interesting to read during this time when we are having another round of sexual assault call out accounts amidst a national reckoning over the meaning of accountability and justice. I&apos;ve been thinking a lot about purity culture and the way it&apos;s been remanifested over again online without christianity. I&apos;ve also been thinking about massive lies and cover ups of the sexual abuse of</span>
  <span id="freeText17776285178419240782" style="display:none">cw sexual assault. Super short play that I read partially because it was short and partially bc I thought it might be interesting to read during this time when we are having another round of sexual assault call out accounts amidst a national reckoning over the meaning of accountability and justice. I've been thinking a lot about purity culture and the way it's been remanifested over again online without christianity. I've also been thinking about massive lies and cover ups of the sexual abuse of children because of the renewed interest in the Epstein case, which has some parallels to the Catholic church scandals. And there's lowkey also some lessons here about the current youtube drama! "Doubt requires more courage than conviction does, and more energy, because conviction is a resting place and doubt is infinite--it is a passionate exercise". I tried to examine my own biases. I automatically assumed the priest was guilty because... well... wouldn't you? Everyone knows the trope of Catholic priests and young boys. The ending confirmed his guilt for me, even though there was no proof. But I'm still wrestling with the morality of the fact that he just got assigned to a new parish. That means there's just a new crop of kids being abused and it's not in front of sister Aloysius's face. I think she knows this and therefore wrestles with wondering what exactly she has accomplished. There were some parallels between this book and the Borrowers that I finished yesterday. In that book the main character kidnapped a child because she suspected he was gay and she knew his evangelical parents were taking him to conversion camp. In this book the mother of the allegedly abused child also thinks her son might be gay and would rather sweep all these problems under the rug if it means he can finish school. The mother in this play had the additional pressure of having the only Black child in an all white school. Idk lots to stew over about the rights of victims and the rights of the accused, esp in situations where the victim's idea of justice differs from what you as someone adjacent to the situation wants. And the rights of parents to decide what is best for their children. Like I was totally on sister alonysis's side for wanting to protect an extremely vulnerable child, but the mother made it clear that this would ruin his life and it's easy for me to say that the abuse would be more of a life ruiner but who has the ultimate say? The sister or the parents? Esp in a situation like this where Aloyonis had absolutely no proof and only a gut feeling, because if anything had been confirmed (not even confirmed, if she had literally anything more to go on) it would be way more straightforward for her to take action and protect the child. (though who knows, the school would've probably intensely suppressed it and the little boy would end up suffering greatly and traumatized further, esp considering the racial dynamics, the mother of the boy probably was thinking along these lines). (And the whole aspect that the boy had been so bullied he had to leave the previous school and the only one " protecting" (grooming??) him here was the priest :/) And then because the theme was doubt I started doubting whether anything even did happen with the priest and the kid! It's so impossible to find truth in anything!! I guess that's the point! I honestly wish it had been longer but maybe now I'll watch the movie, though I guess it achieved the goal of making me stew inside my brain in just 50 pages</span>
  <a data-text-id="17776285178419240782" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


